'''Charles Edward Manoharan "Mano" Ponniah''' (born 3 May 1943, [[Kalutara]], [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]]) is a Sri Lankan architect who played [[first-class cricket]] in Sri Lanka and England from 1964 to 1969.

==Cricket career in Ceylon==
Mano Ponniah attended [[S. Thomas' College, Mount Lavinia]], before studying engineering at the [[University of Ceylon]]. He was a member of the University team that won the [[Premier Trophy|P. Saravanamuttu Trophy]] in 1963.<ref>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2010/01/31/SPO40.ASP Mano Ponniah: Bashful Batsman and Articulate Architect]</ref>

He played for Ceylon as an opening batsman while still a student, making his first-class debut in the [[Gopalan Trophy]] match against [[Tamil Nadu cricket team|Madras]] in 1963-64, when in 76.1 overs in the second innings he made 60 not out, Ceylon's highest score of the match, to help Ceylon to victory by six wickets.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/26/26616.html Ceylon Board President's XI v Madras 1963-64]</ref> He toured India with Ceylon in 1964-65, playing in seven of the eight first-class matches and scoring 325 runs at an average of 25.00.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/1/Ceylon_in_India_1964-65/f_Ceylon_Batting.html Batting averages, Ceylon in India 1964-65]</ref> He played in all three matches against India.

==Cricket career in England==
In 1966 he went to [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]], to continue his studies. He played for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]] from 1967 to 1969. His best season was 1967, when in 13 matches he scored 800 runs at an average of 36.36.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26386/f_Batting_by_Season.html CEM Ponniah batting by season]</ref> His highest score in 1967 was 98 not out against [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]], when he opened the innings and added 194 for the second wicket with [[Roger Knight]].<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/28/28714.html Cambridge University v Middlesex 1967]</ref> In 1968 Cambridge won no matches, and "despite a rather limited range of strokes"<ref>''[[Wisden]]'' 1969, p. 683.</ref> Ponniah scored their only century. In the match against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] he made 101 not out in the first innings and 67 in the second, while his team-mates made only 93 and 63 respectively.<ref>[http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29451.html Cambridge University v Lancashire 1968]</ref> In his last match, against [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]] in 1969, he made 27 and 50 not out, sharing an unbroken third-wicket partnership of 123 in 92 minutes with Knight.<ref>''Wisden'' 1970, p. 349.</ref>

==Architecture career==
Ponniah worked in England until 1990, when he returned to Sri Lanka and founded the Colombo architectural firm Mano Ponniah & Associates. The firm has won several awards, including one for an ocean resort in the [[Maldives]].<ref>[http://mpa-arch.com/index.html Mano Ponniah & Associates website]</ref>

He and his wife Radhika, whom he married in 1971, have two sons.

